'''Kristin Dawn Chenoweth''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|tʃ|ɛ|n|oʊ|w|ɛ|θ}}; born '''Kristi Dawn Chenoweth'''; July 24, 1968)<ref name=biochannel>[http://www.biography.com/people/kristin-chenoweth-20631919 Kristin Chenoweth Biography], ''[[The Biography Channel]]'' [[A&E Networks]], accessed December 1, 2014; according to her autobiography, she was named Kristi Dawn Chenoweth upon her adoption five days after her birth.</ref> is an American actress and singer, with credits in [[musical theatre]], film, and television. In 1999, she won a [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actress in a Musical]] for her performance as [[Sally Brown]] in ''[[You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown]]'' on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]. In 2003, Chenoweth was nominated for a second [[Tony Award]] for originating the role of [[Glinda]] in the musical ''[[Wicked (musical)|Wicked]]''. Her television roles include [[Annabeth Schott]] in NBC's ''[[The West Wing]]'' and [[Olive Snook]] on the [[comedy drama]] ''[[Pushing Daisies]]'', for which she won a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]] in 2009.

Chenoweth sang [[gospel music]] as a child in [[Oklahoma]] and studied [[opera]] before deciding to pursue a career in musical theatre. In 1997, she made her Broadway debut in ''[[Steel Pier (musical)|Steel Pier]]'', winning a [[Theatre World Award]]. Her other Broadway credits include ''[[The Apple Tree]]'' in 2006, ''[[Promises, Promises (musical)|Promises, Promises]]'' in 2010 and ''[[On the Twentieth Century]]'' in 2015, for which she received a third [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Musical|Tony Award]] nomination. She has also appeared in five City Center [[Encores!]] productions, [[Off-Broadway]], and in [[Regional theater in the United States|regional theatre]].

Chenoweth had her own sitcom, ''[[Kristin (TV series)|Kristin]]'', in 2001, and has guest-starred on many shows, including ''[[Sesame Street]]'' and ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'', for which she was nominated for Emmy Awards in 2010 and 2011. She also starred in the ABC TV series ''[[GCB (TV series)|GCB]]'' in 2012, played Lavinia in ''[[Trial & Error (TV series)|Trial & Error]]'' in 2018, and played the characters Mildred Layton and Miss Codwell in the musical comedy series ''[[Schmigadoon!]]'' in 2021 and 2023, respectively. In films, she has played mostly character roles, such as in ''[[Bewitched (2005 film)|Bewitched]]'' (2005), ''[[The Pink Panther (2006 film)|The Pink Panther]]'' (2006) and ''[[RV (film)|RV]]'' (2006). She has played roles in made-for-TV movies, such as ''[[Descendants (2015 film)|Descendants]]'' (2015) and several Christmas-themed ones; done voice work in animated films such as ''[[Rio 2]]'' (2014) and ''[[The Peanuts Movie]]'' (2015) along with the animated TV series ''[[Sit Down, Shut Up (2009 TV series)|Sit Down, Shut Up]]'' and ''[[BoJack Horseman]]''; hosted several award shows; and released several albums of songs, including ''[[A Lovely Way to Spend Christmas]]'' (2008), ''[[Some Lessons Learned]]'' (2011), ''[[Coming Home (Kristin Chenoweth album)|Coming Home]]'' (2014), ''[[The Art of Elegance]]'' (2016) and ''[[For the Girls]]'' (2019). Chenoweth also wrote a 2009 memoir, ''[[A Little Bit Wicked]]''.

==Early life==
Chenoweth was adopted when she was five days old by Junie Smith Chenoweth and Jerry Morris Chenoweth, both [[chemical engineering|chemical engineers]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=66b9V9qRb1k |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211222/66b9V9qRb1k |archive-date=December 22, 2021 |url-status=live|work=SAG-AFTRA Foundation|title=Kristin Chenoweth|series=Conversations|date=May 22, 2015|access-date=October 2, 2016}}{{cbignore}}</ref> from [[Broken Arrow, Oklahoma]], a suburb of [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]],<ref>Chenoweth, Chapters 1 and 5</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kchenoweth.net/kristin_biography.php|title=Kristin Dawn Chenoweth|publisher=KChenoweth.Net|access-date=October 13, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425062911/http://kchenoweth.net/kristin_biography.php|archive-date=April 25, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>Randall, Henry P. [https://books.google.com/books?id=-NorAQAAIAAJ ''Who's who among students in American universities and colleges''], vol. 57, Randall Publishing Co., 1991, p. 249, accessed August 29, 2012</ref> and named Kristi Dawn Chenoweth.<ref>Chenoweth (2009), Chapters 4 and 5. On the advice of her voice teacher, [[Florence Birdwell]], she added the "n" at the end of her first name, hoping that it would make people take her more seriously as an opera singer. See Beaujon, Ewa. [https://web.archive.org/web/20100612043021/http://www.expressnightout.com/content/2009/04/kristin_chenoweth.php "Keeping it Clean: Kristin Chenoweth, 'A Little Bit Wicked{{'"}}]. expressnightout.com, {{Nowrap|April 13}}, 2009</ref> She revealed in her 2023 book ''I'm No Philosopher, but I Got Thoughts'' that her biological parents were [[bassist]] Billy Ethridge (briefly a member of [[ZZ Top]]) and "Mama Lynn".<ref>Chenoweth (2023), p. 189</ref> She has stated that she is of one quarter [[Cherokee descent]]<ref>[[James Brady (columnist)|Brady, James]]. [https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/221760271 "In Step With Kristin Chenoweth"], ''[[Arizona Daily Star]]'', May 15, 2005, p. 138, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> and that she eventually met her biological mother.<ref>[https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/VIDEO-Kristin-Chenoweth-Sings-Somewhere-Over-the-Rainbow-Accompanied-by-Katie-Couric-on-Piano-20191206 "Video: Kristin Chenoweth Sings 'Somewhere Over the Rainbow' Accompanied by Katie Couric on Piano"], BroadwayWorld.com, December 6, 2019</ref> At an early age, she performed gospel songs for local churches. A performing highlight of her childhood was a solo appearance at the [[Southern Baptist Convention]] national conference at the age of 12, where she performed the [[Evie (singer)|Evie]] song "Four Feet Eleven". The chorus begins, "I'm only 4 feet 11, but I'm going to Heaven" (Chenoweth is {{convert|4|ft|11|in|cm|abbr=on}} in height).<ref name=tcm>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/805677%7C0/Kristin-Chenoweth/biography.html|publisher=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|title=Biography}}</ref>  After graduating from [[Broken Arrow Senior High School]], where she participated in school plays, Chenoweth attended [[Oklahoma City University]], where she was a member of [[Gamma Phi Beta]] (Beta Omicron) sorority.<ref>[http://www.eduinreview.com/resources/gamma-phi-beta/ Gamma Phi Beta Sorority] eduinreview.com, accessed {{Nowrap|March 8}}, 2010.</ref> She earned a bachelor's degree in [[musical theatre]] in 1990<ref name=NPR2009>{{cite news|work=[[Fresh Air]]|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=103147489|title=April&nbsp;16, 2009}}</ref><ref name=Allen>Allen, Silas. [http://newsok.com/kristin-chenoweth-says-success-is-a-combination-of-training-ambition/article/3808891 "Kristin Chenoweth says success is a combination of training, ambition"], NewsOK.com, May 12, 2013, accessed December 5, 2014</ref> and a master's degree in opera performance in 1992,<ref name=Allen/><ref>[http://newsok.com/article/3806024 "Oklahoma City University to Honor Kristin Chenoweth at Spring Commencement"], ''The Oklahoman'', May 3, 2013, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> studying under voice instructor and mentor, [[Florence Birdwell]].<ref name=NPR2009/><ref name=okcu>[http://www.okcu.edu/directory/florence-birdwell "Florence Birdwell, Emeritus Professor of Music"], Oklahoma City University, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> While at OCU, Chenoweth competed in beauty pageants, winning the title of Miss OCU and was the second runner-up in the [[Miss Oklahoma]] pageant in 1991.<ref name=tcm/><ref>Chenoweth (2009), chapter 3</ref> In 1992, Chenoweth participated in a studio recording of ''[[The Most Happy Fella]]''.<ref name=Kristinofficial>{{cite web|title=Kristin Chenoweth| url=http://www.officialkristinchenoweth.com|website=Officialkristinchenoweth.com|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref>

While she was in college and working towards her master's degree, Chenoweth performed at the Lyric Theatre in [[Oklahoma City]], among other [[Regional theater in the United States|regional theatres]], in roles like June in ''[[Gypsy (musical)|Gypsy]]'', Liesl in ''[[The Sound of Music]]'', Fran in ''[[Promises, Promises (musical)|Promises, Promises]]''<ref>Rogers, Rick. [http://newsok.com/lyric-production-keeps-promises-to-lift-spirits-of-tired-businessmen/article/2322990 "Lyric Production Keeps Promises to Lift Spirits of Tired Businessmen"], NewsOK.com, July 5, 1990, accessed December 5, 2014</ref> and Tuptim in ''[[The King and I]]''.<ref>Curtright, Bob. [http://www.kansas.com/entertainment/arts-culture/article1118494.html "Getting to know a more culturally accurate ''King and I'' at MTW"], ''The Wichita Eagle'', July 7, 2013, accessed December 5, 2014</ref> As she completed her master's degree, Chenoweth participated in several vocal competitions and was named "most promising up-and-coming singer" in the [[Metropolitan Opera]] National Council auditions, which came with a full scholarship to [[Philadelphia]]'s [[Academy of Vocal Arts]].<ref name=Culwell>Culwell-Block, Logan. [http://www.playbill.com/article/over-20-years-of-popular-kristin-chenoweth-on-stage-and-screen-com-340972 "Over 20 Years of Popular: Kristin Chenoweth on Stage and Screen"], ''Playbill'', February 7, 2015, February 12, 2017</ref> Two weeks before school started, however, she went to New York City to help a friend move. While there, she auditioned for the 1993 [[Paper Mill Playhouse]] production of the musical ''[[Animal Crackers (musical)|Animal Crackers]]'' and was cast in the role of Arabella Rittenhouse. She turned down the scholarship and moved to New York to play the role and pursue a career in musical theatre.<ref name=Culwell/><ref name=HollywoodWalk/>

==Career==
{{Further|Kristin Chenoweth credits}}

===Theatre===
After ''Animal Crackers'', Chenoweth continued to appear in [[Regional theater in the United States|regional theatre]] productions, such as ''[[Babes in Arms]]'' at [[The Guthrie Theater]] in [[Minneapolis]],<ref>[https://ovrtur.com/production/2896409 "''Babes in Arms''"], Ovrtur.com, accessed October 1, 2024</ref> and ''[[Phantom (musical)|Phantom]]'' (as Christine; she also toured in Germany in this role),<ref>Johnson, Lottie Elizabeth. [https://www.deseret.com/entertainment/2019/10/25/20927670/phantom-of-the-opera-broadway-andrew-lloyd-webber-phantom-maury-yeston-utah-hale-centre-theatre "The ''Phantom of the Opera'' story that never made it to Broadway teaches us something about villains"], ''Deseret News'', October 25, 2019</ref> playing roles in [[Off-Broadway]] productions like Luisa in ''[[The Fantasticks]]''<ref name=tcm/><ref name=Carnegie2014>Suskin, Steven. [https://www.playbill.com/article/kristin-chenoweth-returns-to-carnegie-hall-with-the-evolution-of-a-soprano-com-218003 "Kristin Chenoweth Returns to Carnegie Hall with ''The Evolution of a Soprano''"], ''Playbill'', May 5, 2014</ref> and Kristy in ''Box Office of the Damned'' (both in 1994).<ref>[https://www.newyorktheatreguide.com/stars-on-stage/kristin-chenoweth "Kristen Chenoweth"], ''New York Theatre Guide'', accessed October 1, 2024</ref> In 1997, she appeared as Hyacinth in the [[Roundabout Theater Company]] production of [[Moliere]]'s farcical ''[[Les Fourberies de Scapin|Scapin]]'', earning her first ''[[New York Times]]'' review, with [[Ben Brantley]] writing "Kristin Chenoweth's sob-prone ingenue&nbsp;is delightful".<ref>Brantley, Ben. [http://theater.nytimes.com/mem/theater/treview.html?html_title=&tols_title=SCAPIN%20(PLAY)&pdate=19970110&byline=By%20BEN%20BRANTLEY&id=1077011431344 "M. Moliere, Meet Mr. Irwin. He Clowns Around a Bit, Too"]. ''The New York Times'', {{Nowrap|January 10}}, 1997, accessed {{Nowrap|April 28}}, 2010.</ref> She made her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut in the spring of 1997 as Precious McGuire in the musical ''[[Steel Pier (musical)|Steel Pier]]'' by [[Kander and Ebb]], for which she won a [[Theatre World Award]].<ref name=tcm/> In 1998 she reprised one of her regional theatre roles, Anne Draper,<ref>[https://www.abouttheartists.com/productions/50935-strike-up-the-band-at-goodspeed-opera-house-1995 "''Strike Up the Band''"], About the Artists, accessed April 21, 2024</ref> in the [[Encores!|City Center Encores!]] staged concert of the [[George Gershwin|George]] and [[Ira Gershwin]] musical ''[[Strike Up the Band (musical)|Strike Up the Band]]''.<ref>Brantley, Ben. [http://theater.nytimes.com/mem/theater/treview.html?html_title=&tols_title=STRIKE%20UP%20THE%20BAND%20(PLAY)&pdate=19980214&byline=By%20BEN%20BRANTLEY&id=1077011431588 "Theater Review: Jingoism Parodied: Gershwins' War of '27"]. ''The New York Times'', February 14, 1998</ref> and created roles in the original [[Lincoln Center Theater]] production of [[William Finn]]'s ''[[A New Brain]]''.<ref>[http://www.lct.org/showMain.htm?id=133 "Lincoln Center, 'A New Brain'"]. LCT.org, accessed April 6, 2011</ref> [[Ben Rimalower]], in ''Playbill'', wrote: "It's unlikely anyone will equal Kristin Chenoweth in the role of 'Nancy D., the waitress.'"<ref name=Rimalower>Rimalower, Ben. [http://www.playbill.com/article/let-yourself-go-the-11-kristin-chenoweth-cds-you-should-know-com-332672 "''Let Yourself Go'': The 11 Kristin Chenoweth CDs You Should Know"], ''Playbill'', October 11, 2014, accessed February 12, 2017</ref>

[[File:Laura Bush, Kristin Chenoweth, and models.jpg|thumb|300px|Chenoweth (holding her dog, Madeline Kahn "Maddie" Chenoweth) with [[Laura Bush]] and celebrity models in the 2007 Red Dress Collection Celebrity Fashion Show to raise awareness of heart disease]]
Chenoweth played [[Sally Brown]], the title character's little sister, in the 1999 Broadway revival of ''[[You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown]]''. Sally was not present in the original production. Chenoweth won [[Tony Award|Tony]] and [[Drama Desk Award]]s for Best Featured Actress in a Musical for her performance.<ref>[http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=5211 "''You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'', Ambassador Theatre, Broadway, 1999"].  IBDB.com, accessed {{Nowrap|May 14}}, 2012.</ref> Later that year, she starred on Broadway in the short-lived comic play ''[[Epic Proportions]]'',<ref>[http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=9682 "Epic Proportions listing, Helen Hayes Theatre, Broadway, 1999"] ibdb.com, accessed {{Nowrap|March 7}}, 2010.</ref> followed by starring as Daisy Gamble in the Encores! production of ''[[On a Clear Day You Can See Forever]]'' in {{Nowrap|February 2000}}.<ref>Brantley, Ben. [http://theater.nytimes.com/mem/theater/treview.html?html_title=&tols_title=ON%20A%20CLEAR%20DAY%20YOU%20CAN%20SEE%20FOREVER%20(PLAY)&byline=By%20BEN% "Theater Review; Reincarnation With a Green Thumb"]. ''The New York Times'', {{Nowrap|February 12}}, 2000</ref>

After this, Chenoweth split her time between stage and TV or film roles and released her first solo album, ''Let Yourself Go'' (2001). In 2002, she performed in the City Center Encores! ''10th Anniversary Bash''.<ref>[[Robert Simonson|Simonson, Robert]]; Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/article/chenoweth-ebersole-errico-neuwirth-expected-for-encores-bash-nov-24-25-com-109306 "Chenoweth, Ebersole, Errico, Neuwirth Expected for Encores! Bash Nov. 24–25"], Playbill.com, November 1, 2002, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> In October&nbsp;2003, she returned to Broadway (after the San Francisco tryout) in the musical ''[[Wicked (musical)|Wicked]]'', as [[Glinda the Good Witch]]. She was nominated for a 2004 Tony Award as [[Tony Award for Best Leading Actress in a Musical|Best Leading Actress in a Musical]] for her performance; her co-star [[Idina Menzel]] (who played [[Elphaba]], the [[Wicked Witch of the West]]) won the award.<ref>[http://broadwayworld.com/tonyawardsyear.cfm?year=2004 "Tony Awards, 2004"]. Broadwayworld.com, accessed April 6, 2011</ref> Chenoweth was also nominated for the [[Drama Desk Award]]<ref>Gans, Andrew; Simonson, Robert; Allen, Morgan. [http://www.playbill.com/article/2003-04-drama-desk-award-nominations-announced-wicked-leads-pack-with-11-nominations-com-119391 "Drama Desk Award Nominations Announced; 'Wicked' Leads Pack with 11 Nominations"], Playbill.com, April 29, 2004, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> and the [[Drama League Award]] for this role.<ref>Simonson, Robert. [http://www.playbill.com/article/drama-league-announces-roster-of-honorees-com-119328 "Drama League Announces Roster of Honorees"], Playbill.com, April 23, 2004, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> Ben Rimalower, in ''Playbill'', wrote that, for Glinda, "the gold standard was unquestionably and indelibly set" by Chenoweth's performances.<ref name=Rimalower/> After playing Glinda for nine months, Chenoweth left ''Wicked'', on {{Nowrap|July 18}}, 2004,<ref>Simonson, Robert. [http://www.playbill.com/article/original-glindas-bubble-floats-away-july-18-when-chenoweth-leaves-broadways-wicked-com-120850 "Original Glinda's Bubble Floats Away {{Nowrap|July 18}} When Chenoweth Leaves Broadway's ''Wicked''"]. Playbill.com, {{Nowrap|July 18}}, 2004</ref> soon joining the cast of ''[[The West Wing]]'' in Los Angeles.<ref name=Culwell/> The ''Wicked'' cast album earned a 2005 [[Grammy Award]].<ref>{{Cite news|first=Kenneth |last=Jones | title=''Wicked''{{'}}s Cast Album Wins Grammy Award |date=February 13, 2005|url =http://www.playbill.com/article/wickeds-cast-album-wins-grammy-award-com-124172 |work=Playbill | access-date =February 12, 2017}}</ref>

Chenoweth played [[Cunegonde]] in the [[New York Philharmonic]] revival of ''[[Candide (musical)|Candide]]'', directed by [[Lonny Price]], in {{Nowrap|May 2004}}.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U5liuHR6wug Chenoweth performing "Glitter and Be Gay"].  YouTube.com, accessed {{Nowrap|October 7}}, 2010</ref> The production was also broadcast on [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]]'s ''[[Great Performances]]''. A performance of the rarely sung duet "We Are Women", between Cunegonde and the Old Lady (played by [[Patti Lupone]]), was included in the production.<ref name=HollywoodWalk/><ref>Tommasini, Anthony. [http://theater.nytimes.com/mem/theater/treview.html?res=9B03EEDC163CF934A35756C0A9629C8B63 "Music Review: Voltaire Via Bernstein, Donald Trump Reference Included"]. ''The New York Times'', {{Nowrap|May 7}}, 2004</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=giRppPYWcgc Chenoweth and LuPone performing "We Are Women"]. YouTube.com, accessed {{Nowrap|October 7}}, 2010</ref>

From December 2006 to March 2007, following a 2005 Encores! presentation of the piece, Chenoweth starred on Broadway as Eve in a revival of ''[[The Apple Tree]]'' with co-stars [[Brian d'Arcy James]] and former fiancé [[Marc Kudisch]].<ref>Hernandez, Ernio. [http://www.playbill.com/article/a-tree-grows-on-broadway-chenoweth-james-and-kudisch-open-the-apple-tree-com-137016 "A Tree Grows on Broadway: Chenoweth, James and Kudisch Open ''The Apple Tree''"], Playbill.com, December 14, 2006, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> She received nominations for the [[Drama Desk Award]]<ref name=nom>Gans, Andrew; Pincus-Roth, Zachary. [http://www.playbill.com/article/nominees-for-drama-desk-awards-announced-lovemusik-garners-12-noms-com-140369 "Nominees for Drama Desk Awards Announced; ''LoveMusik'' Garners 12 Noms"], Playbill.com, April 26, 2007, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> and the [[Drama League Award]]. She hosted the 2007 [[Drama Desk Award]]s ceremony.<ref name=nom/> The same year, she played Female Star in the 2007 Encores! presentation of ''Stairway to Paradise''<ref>Gans, Andrew. [https://playbill.com/article/chenoweth-chamberlin-and-more-build-a-stairway-to-paradise-beginning-may-10-com-140686 "Chenoweth, Chamberlin and More Build a Stairway to Paradise Beginning May 10"], ''Playbill'', May 10, 2007</ref> and returned for her fifth Encores! production in [[Jerome Kern]] and [[Oscar Hammerstein&nbsp;II]]'s ''[[Music in the Air]]'' in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gans|first=Andrew|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/theres-music-in-the-air-at-city-center-beginning-feb-5-com-157676| title=There's ''Music in the Air'' at City Center Beginning Feb. 5| work=Playbill|date=February 5, 2009 |access-date=February 12, 2017}}</ref> Chenoweth was scheduled to return to The Metropolitan Opera in 2010 to play Samira in [[John Corigliano]]'s opera ''[[The Ghosts of Versailles]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Simonson |first=Robert |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/met-opera-seeks-chenoweth-for-the-ghosts-of-versailles-com-130859 |title=Met Opera Seeks Chenoweth for ''The Ghosts of Versailles'' |work=Playbill.com |date=February 14, 2006 |access-date=February 12, 2017}}</ref> The Met canceled the expensive production in 2008 as the U.S. economy weakened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bad economy affects The Met: Kristen Chenoweth's opera debut cancelled |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2008-11-14/news/17911501_1_less-costly-revival-john-corigliano-peter-gelb |website=New York Daily News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730141309/http://articles.nydailynews.com/2008-11-14/news/17911501_1_less-costly-revival-john-corigliano-peter-gelb |archive-date=July 30, 2012 |date=November 14, 2008}}</ref>

In 2009, Chenoweth was part of the rotating ensemble cast of [[Nora Ephron|Nora]] and [[Delia Ephron]]'s ''[[Love, Loss, and What I Wore]]'' [[off-Broadway]] at the [[Westside Theater]].<ref>{{cite web|
url=https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117941288?refcatid=33|title=Love, Loss, and What I Wore|access-date=April 21, 2011|date=October 1, 2009|author=Stasio, Marilyn|work=Variety}}</ref> She next starred as Fran Kubelik in the 2010 Broadway revival of the musical ''[[Promises, Promises (musical)|Promises, Promises]]'', opposite [[Sean Hayes (actor)|Sean Hayes]], which opened on {{Nowrap|April 25}}, 2010.<ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/article/promises-promises-revival-has-a-prayer-and-a-home-com-167200 "''Promises, Promises'' Revival Has a 'Prayer' and a 'Home'"], Playbill.com, {{Nowrap|March 29}}, 2010, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> The songs "[[I Say a Little Prayer]]" and "[[A House Is Not a Home (song)|A House Is Not a Home]]" were added for her to sing.<ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/article/kristin-chenoweth-and-sean-hayes-make-promises-on-broadway-beginning-march-27-com-167159 "Kristin Chenoweth and Sean Hayes Make ''Promises'' on Broadway Beginning {{Nowrap|March 27}}"], Playbill.com, {{Nowrap|March 27}}, 2010, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> Chenoweth and Hayes remained in the cast until the show closed on January 2, 2011,<ref name=extend>Hetrick, Adam and Andrew Gans. [http://www.playbill.com/article/broadway-revival-of-promises-promises-to-close-com-171846 "Broadway Revival of ''Promises, Promises'' to Close"], Playbill.com, September 10, 2010, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> although she missed performances from December 29, 2010, to January 1, 2011, to perform a New Year's Eve concert at Walt Disney Concert Hall on December 31, 2010.<ref name=extend/><ref>Ng, David. [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2010/12/kristin-chenoweth-talks-about-broadway-glee-and-her-new-album.html "Culture Monster: Kristin Chenoweth Talks About Broadway Glee and Her New Album"]. December 30, 2010</ref> She played televangelist [[Tammy Faye Bakker]] in a reading of the musical ''Rise'' in 2011.<ref>{{cite web | last=Culwell-Block | first=Logan | title=Kristin Chenoweth on Why She's Bringing the Story of Tammy Faye Bakker to the Stage | website=Playbill | date=January 18, 2019 | url=https://playbill.com/article/kristin-chenoweth-on-why-shes-bringing-the-story-of-tammy-faye-bakker-to-the-stage | access-date=May 28, 2023}}</ref>

Chenoweth played Lily Garland in a Broadway revival of ''[[On the Twentieth Century]]'', opposite [[Peter Gallagher]], which began previews on February 12 and opened on March 12, 2015, for a 22-week limited engagement through July 19, 2015, at the [[Roundabout Theatre Company]].<ref>Gioia, Michael. [http://www.playbill.com/article/on-the-twentieth-century-with-kristin-chenoweth-and-peter-gallagher-sets-2015-broadway-opening-com-218284 "''On the Twentieth Century'', with Kristin Chenoweth and Peter Gallagher, Sets 2015 Broadway Opening"], Playbill.com, May 14, 2014, accessed February 12, 2017</ref><ref>Gans, Andrew. [https://www.playbill.com/article/on-the-twentieth-century-revival-starring-kristin-chenoweth-extends-on-broadway-com-348027 "''On the Twentieth Century'' Revival, Starring Kristin Chenoweth, Extends on Broadway"], Playbill, April 30, 2015</ref> [[Ben Brantley]] of ''The New York Times'' wrote that Chenoweth "uses [her character's] histrionics to create one of the most virtuosic portraits in song ever on Broadway. The vocal vocabulary she deploys here ranges from jazz-baby brass to operatic silver, often in a single number, and she switches among them with jaw-dropping ease.&nbsp;And every perfectly weighted note is set off by an impeccably exaggerated gesture."<ref>Brantley, Ben. [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/16/theater/review-on-the-twentieth-century-with-kristin-chenoweth-opens-on-broadway.html "Review: ''On the Twentieth Century'', With Kristin Chenoweth, Opens on Broadway"], ''The New York Times'', March 15, 2015</ref> She was nominated for a Tony Award and won another Drama Desk Award for her performance.<ref>McRady, Rachel. [http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/tony-awards-2015-list-winners-201576 "Tony Awards 2015: Complete List of Winners!"], ''[[Us Weekly]]'', June 7, 2015</ref><ref>Levitt, Hayley. [http://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/news/2015-drama-desk-award-winners-are-announced_73086.html "2015 Drama Desk Award Winners Are Announced!"], TheaterMania, May 31, 2015</ref> In November 2023, Chenoweth made a cameo appearance in ''[[Gutenberg! The Musical!]]'' as The Producer<ref>Wild, Stephi. [https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Video-Kristin-Chenoweth-Joins-GUTENBERG-THE-MUSICAL-as-Producer-20231204 "Video: Kristin Chenoweth Joins ''Gutenberg! The Musical!'' as 'Producer'"], BroadwayWorld, December 4, 2023</ref> She co-produced and stars as the title character, [[Jackie Siegel]], in the musical ''[[The Queen of Versailles (musical)|The Queen of Versailles]]'', with music and lyrics by [[Stephen Schwartz]], which premiered at [[Colonial Theatre (Boston)|Colonial Theatre]] in [[Boston]], Massachusetts, in July 2024.<ref>Cortez, Benjamin. [https://hoodline.com/2024/07/kristin-chenoweth-shines-in-pre-broadway-premiere-of-the-queen-of-versailles-at-boston-s-emerson-colonial-theatre "Kristin Chenoweth Shines in Pre-Broadway Premiere of ''The Queen of Versailles'' at Boston's Emerson Colonial Theatre"], Hoodline, July 16, 2024</ref><ref>Wild, Stephi. [https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Pre-Broadway-Run-of-Kristin-Chenoweth-Led-THE-QUEEN-OF-VERSAILLES-Extends-Plus-Complete-Casting-20240513 "Pre-Broadway Run of Kristin Chenoweth-Led ''The Queen of Versailles'' Extends; Plus Complete Casting!"], BroadwayWorld.com, May 13, 2024</ref>

===Television===
After a guest appearance on ''[[LateLine]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |last=Schneider |first=Michael |date=2008-12-19 |title=Kristin Chenoweth joins 'Legally Mad' |url=https://variety.com/2008/scene/markets-festivals/kristin-chenoweth-joins-legally-mad-1117997636/ |access-date=2024-05-31 |website=Variety}}</ref> a role in the short-lived television series ''Paramour'' (1999), and several roles in [[television films]] such as ''[[Annie (1999 film)|Annie]]'' (as Lily St. Regis), Chenoweth starred in her own [[NBC]] [[sitcom]], the semi-autobiographical ''[[Kristin (TV series)|Kristin]]'' in 2001. Thirteen episodes were filmed, but only six aired before it was canceled.<ref>Wren, Celia. [https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/29/theater/theater-trying-to-act-saintly-nowadays-can-be-a-hair-shirt.html "Theater: Trying to Act Saintly Nowadays Can Be a Hair Shirt"]. ''The New York Times'', {{Nowrap|July 29}}, 2001</ref> Chenoweth appeared in the lead role of Marian in the 2003 television film, ''[[The Music Man (2003 film)|The Music Man]]'', opposite [[Matthew Broderick]].<ref name=Best>Symchuk, Adam. [https://movieweb.com/best-kristin-chenoweth-performances-ranked "Best Kristin Chenoweth Performances, Ranked"], ''Movie Web'', September 16, 2023</ref><ref>Simonson, Robert. [http://www.playbill.com/article/broderick-and-chenoweth-give-iowa-a-try-in-music-man-tv-movie-feb-16-com-111554 "Broderick and Chenoweth Give Iowa a Try in ''Music Man'' TV Movie, Feb. 16"], ''Playbill'', February 13, 2003, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> She also guest-starred on such shows as ''[[Frasier]]'' (2001), ''[[Baby Bob]]'' (2002), ''[[Fillmore!]] (2003), ''[[Elmo's World]]'' and ''[[Sesame Street]]'' (several times as Mrs. Noodle) and ''[[Ugly Betty]]'' (2007).<ref>[https://www.broadwayworld.com/people/Kristin-Chenoweth "Kristin Chenoweth"], BroadwayWorld.com, accessed April 26, 2024</ref><ref>Gikow, Louise A. (2009). ''Sesame Street: A Celebration – Forty Years of Life on the Street'', New York: Black Dog & Leventhal Publishers, p. 169 {{ISBN|978-1-57912-638-4}}</ref>

In 2004, Chenoweth began playing the recurring role of media consultant [[Annabeth Schott]] in ''[[The West Wing]]''.<ref name=Culwell/> For her performance, she was nominated twice, along with the cast, for [[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s. She appeared in the final two seasons of the program through 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0155693/filmoseries#tt0200276|title=The West Wing, Chenoweth Credits, 2004–2006|website=IMDb.com|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> Chenoweth had been considered originally for the role of [[Ainsley Hayes]], but she had already accepted her role in ''Wicked''.<ref>Chenoweth (2009), [https://books.google.com/books?id=_JoQGP4wKY8C&pg=PT237 p. 237]</ref> Another of Chenoweth's Christmas-themed TV films was ''[[12 Men of Christmas]]'' (2009); though it received lukewarm reviews, a ''Variety'' review praised Chenoweth, saying "with the right talent, it's possible to make even the moldiest of material sing just a little".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2009/scene/markets-festivals/12-men-of-christmas-1200478038/ |title=12 Men of Christmas|last=Lowry|first=Brian|date=2 December 2009|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=April 26, 2024}}</ref>

[[File:Kristin Chenoweth - 2012 Drama League Benefit Gala (2).jpg|right|thumb|Chenoweth at the 2012<br>[[Drama League of New York|Drama League]] Benefit Gala]]
From 2007 to 2009, Chenoweth played [[Olive Snook]] in the television series, ''[[Pushing Daisies]]''. For her performance, she "became a favorite for her musical numbers and bright personality"<ref name=Best/> and was nominated two years in a row for an [[Emmy Award]],<ref>[http://www.emmys.com/celebrities/kristin-chenoweth Kristin Chenoweth], Emmys.com, accessed December 26, 2011</ref> winning in 2009 as [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress – Comedy Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Joyce Eng|title=Kristin Chenoweth, Jon Cryer Win First Emmys|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Kristin-Chenoweth-Jon-1009931.aspx|work=TVGuide.com|date=September 20, 2009|access-date=September 20, 2009}}</ref> The series was canceled after two seasons.<ref name=tcm/> In 2009, Chenoweth lent her voice to the animated comedy series ''[[Sit Down, Shut Up (2009 TV series)|Sit Down, Shut Up]]'', as Miracle Grohe, a science teacher who does not believe in science.<ref name=NPR2009/> The series lasted just thirteen episodes. Later that year, Chenoweth began a recurring role as [[April Rhodes]] in ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'', singing several songs, earning enthusiastic notices. The character is a former member of the glee club who never finished high school and ended up hitting rock bottom. A review in ''[[USA Today]]'' observed, "Her presence may not make much sense, but if it means hearing Chenoweth sing, we can put up with any explanation the show cares to offer."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/columnist/criticscorner/2009-09-29-critics-corner_N.htm|title=Critic's Corner Wednesday| last=Bianco| first=Robert|date=September 30, 2009|work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|access-date=October 1, 2009}}</ref><ref>See also {{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2009/10/01/glee-season-1-episode-4-tv-recap|title="Glee" Season 1, Episode 4: TV Recap|last=Flandez|first=Raymund| date=October 1, 2009|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=October 1, 2009}}, {{cite web|url=http://uk.tv.ign.com/articles/103/1030649p1.html|title=Glee: "The Rhodes Not Taken" Review|last=Goldman|first=Eric|date=October 1, 2009|website=IGN|access-date=October 28, 2009}} and {{cite news| url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2009/09/glee--1.html|title='Glee': The top 5 reasons to rewatch 'The Rhodes Not Taken'|last=Martin|first=Denise| date=October 1, 2009|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=October 1, 2009}}</ref> She received a [[Satellite Award]] for Outstanding Guest Star.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000296/ Satellite Awards, 2009]. imdb.com, accessed {{Nowrap|April 28}}, 2010.</ref>

In 2010, Chenoweth returned to ''Glee'' as April Rhodes, singing more songs.<ref>Stack, Tim. [http://popwatch.ew.com/2009/10/26/glee-kristin-chenoweth-julia-roberts "''Glee'': Kristin Chenoweth to return!"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007132557/http://popwatch.ew.com/2009/10/26/glee-kristin-chenoweth-julia-roberts |date=October 7, 2011 }} ''Entertainment Weekly'', {{Nowrap|October 26}}, 2009, accessed {{Nowrap|April 27}}, 2010.</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' review commented, "the best part about '[[Home (Glee)|Home]]' was undoubtedly the return of Kristin Chenoweth as April. From her spunky duet of [[Fire (Bruce Springsteen song)|Fire]] with Schue, to the heart-achingly lonely coo of '[[One Less Bell to Answer]]' which segued into a fantastic reprise of '[[A House Is Not a Home (song)|A House Is Not a Home]]' and of course her bone-chilling take on [[Home (The Wiz song)|Home]] I fell in love with her again."<ref>[http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2010/04/glee-home-is-where-the-heart-and-kristin-chenoweth-are.html "''Glee'': 'Home' is where the heart – and Kristin Chenoweth – are"]. ''Los Angeles Times'', {{Nowrap|April 28}}, 2010</ref> She was nominated for both 2010 and 2011 Emmy Awards for her performances on ''Glee''.<ref>[http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/GLEE_Morrison_Michele_More_Receive_2010_Emmy_Noms_20100708 "''Glee'', Morrison, Michele, Tony Awards, Chenoweth & More Receive 2010 Emmy Noms!"], BroadwayWorld.com, {{Nowrap|July 8}}, 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominations/award-search?search_api_views_fulltext=&submit=Search&field_celebrity_details_field_display_name=Kristin+Chenoweth&field_show_details_field_nominee_show_nr_title=&field_show_details_field_network=All&field_show_details_field_production_company=All&field_nominations_year=1949-01-01+00%3A00%3A00&field_nominations_year_1=2017-01-01+00%3A00%3A00&field_award_category=All Kristin Chenoweth nominations], Emmy Awards website, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> Chenoweth returned again to ''Glee'' in "[[Rumours (Glee)|Rumours]]" in 2011,<ref name=TVGuideCredits>[https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/kristin-chenoweth/credits/160972 "Kristin Chenoweth: Credits"], ''TV Guide'', accessed May 3, 2012</ref> and for its 100th episode in 2014.<<ref>{{cite web | last=Nicholson | first=Rebecca | title=Glee marks 100th episode with Paltrow, Chenoweth and original cast | website=the Guardian | date=March 19, 2014 | url=http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/mar/18/glee-marks-100th-episode-paltrow-chenoweth-original-cast-fox | access-date=May 28, 2023}}</ref> In 2011, Chenoweth starred in a pilot for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] called ''Good Christian Bitches'' as Carlene Cockburn.<ref>[https://www.tvguide.com/news/kristin-chenoweth-abc-1030691.aspx?rss=object Kristin Chenoweth Joins ABC's ''Good Christian'' Cast]. TVguide.com</ref> ABC picked up the show and changed the title to ''[[GCB (TV series)|GCB]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.deadline.com/2011/05/abc-starts-new-series-pickups-with-orders-to-tim-allen-and-apt-23/|title=ABC Starts New Series Pickups with Orders to Tim Allen and Apt. 23|magazine=Deadline.com|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva| date=May 13, 2011| access-date=February 12, 2017}}</ref> The series debuted in 2012 but lasted only one season, despite "the cast's comedic wit and strong performances";<ref name=Best/> Chenoweth generally sang a song in each episode.<ref>Bryant, Adam. [https://www.tvguide.com/News/ABC-Cancels-GCB-PanAm-River-Missing-1047428.aspx "ABC Cancels GCB, Pan Am, The River and Missing"], TVGuide.com, May 11, 2012</ref> In 2012, she guest-starred in an episode of the sitcom ''[[Hot in Cleveland]]'', titled "The Gateway Friend".<ref name=TVGuideCredits/>

Chenoweth played a recurring role as Peggy Byrne, a political reporter, in the fourth season of ''[[The Good Wife (TV series)|The Good Wife]]'' (2012).<ref>O'Connell, Michael. [https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/kristin-chenoweth-good-wife-season-4-341773 "Kristin Chenoweth Joins ''The Good Wife'' in Recurring Role"], ''The Hollywood Reporter'', June 26, 2012</ref> However, she soon left the show after sustaining a skull fracture, broken nose, spinal and rib injuries and cracked teeth when she was struck by equipment on the set.<ref name=fracture/> She appeared in the 2012 season opener<ref>Yahr, Emily. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/tv-column/post/kristin-chenoweth-drops-out-of-the-good-wife-role-after-head-injury-on-set/2012/08/13/eeebeba4-e585-11e1-936a-b801f1abab19_blog.html "Kristin Chenoweth drops out of ''The Good Wife'' role after head injury on set"], ''The Washington Post'', August 13, 2012</ref><ref>See [http://www.theindychannel.com/entertainment/kristin-chenoweth-was-inches-from-death-in-the-good-wife-accident_09400394 "Kristin Chenoweth was inches from death in ''The Good Wife'' accident"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202221105/http://www.theindychannel.com/entertainment/kristin-chenoweth-was-inches-from-death-in-the-good-wife-accident_09400394 |date=February 2, 2014 }}, ''The Indy Channel'' (ABC's RTV6), October 1, 2012; and [http://www.hollywood.com/news/Kristin_Chenoweth_cracked_three_teeth_during_The_Good_Wife_accident/42417423 "Kristin Chenoweth cracked three teeth during ''The Good Wife'' accident"], Hollywood.com, October 16, 2012</ref> and returned in a short scene for another episode.<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/01/kristin-chenoweth-returns-good-wife_n_1849340.html Kristin Chenoweth Returns To 'The Good Wife'], ''The Huffington Post'', accessed November 12, 2012</ref> She later expressed regret at not pursuing legal action for her injuries,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Murphy |first=J. Kim |date=2023-01-18 |title=Kristin Chenoweth Was 'Practically Killed' in 'Good Wife' Set Accident, Regrets Not Taking Legal Action: 'Don't Ever Let Fear Rule Your Life' |url=https://variety.com/2023/tv/news/kristin-chenoweth-good-wife-injuries-legal-action-1235492775/ |access-date=2024-08-27 |website=Variety}}</ref> which she said caused her to endure "hundreds of doctor appointments", "head-to-toe pain on a daily basis".<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Walsh |first=Savannah |date=2022-03-25 |title=Kristin Chenoweth Didn't Want to Be "a Problem" for CBS After 'Good Wife' Injury |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2022/03/kristin-chenoweth-didnt-want-to-be-a-problem-for-cbs-after-good-wife-injury |access-date=2024-08-27 |magazine=Vanity Fair}}</ref> anxiety and depression.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Williams |first=Mary Elizabeth |date=2023-01-29 |title="I don't toot glitter": Kristin Chenoweth on embracing her failure, anger and questions for God |url=https://www.salon.com/2023/01/29/i-dont-toot-glitter-kristin-chenoweth-on-embracing-her-failure-anger-and-questions-for-god/ |access-date=2024-08-27 |website=Salon}}</ref> In 2013 and 2014, she made two appearances as Brittany Gold on the TV series, ''[[Kirstie (TV series)|Kirstie]]''.<ref>Abrams, Natalie. [https://www.tvguide.com/news/exclusive-chenoweth-johnston-leachman-kirstie-1066919.aspx "Exclusive: Kristin Chenoweth, Kristen Johnston, Cloris Leachman Head to Kirstie"], ''TV Guide'', June 20, 2013</ref><ref>Kondolojy, Amanda [https://web.archive.org/web/20140118231829/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/01/16/kristin-chenoweth-returns-on-an-all-new-episode-of-kirstie-january-22/229976/ Kristin Chenoweth Returns on an All-New Episode of 'Kirstie' January 22] ''TV by the Numbers'', January 28, 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2013/11/05/tv-lands-december-is-one-to-remember-231515/20131105tvland01/ "TV Land's December Is One to Remember!"], ''The Futon Critic'', November 5, 2013</ref> From 2014 to 2019 she appeared in five episodes of the animated series ''[[BoJack Horseman]]''.<ref name=BoJack>[https://www.vulture.com/2016/07/bojack-horseman-voice-actors-past-present/slideshow/38/ "Here Are the Voices Behind BoJack Horseman, Past and Present"] {{Webarchive| url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915074840/http://www.vulture.com/2016/07/bojack-horseman-voice-actors-past-present/slideshow/38 |date=September 15, 2017 }}, Vulture.com, July 2016, accessed September 10, 2017; and Chappell, Les. [https://www.avclub.com/a-ruthless-bojack-horseman-breaks-the-life-of-princess-1812566899 "A ruthless ''BoJack Horseman'' breaks the life of Princess Carolyn and the heart of its audience"], ''The A.V. Club'', September 16, 2017, accessed November 18, 2017</ref> Chenoweth played [[Maleficent]] in the live-action [[Disney Channel]] original movie, ''[[Descendants (2015 film)|Descendants]]'' (2015). The ''Entertainment Weekly'' reviewer said that "Chenoweth stole much of the show".<ref>Li, Shirley. [https://www.ew.com/article/2015/07/31/descendants-disney-react "''Descendants'' react: Did the tale about junior villains cast a spell?"], ''Entertainment Weekly'', July 31, 2015</ref><ref>Snetiker, Marc. [http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/05/01/kristin-chenoweth-maleficent-descendants/ "Kristin Chenoweth to play Maleficent in Disney's original movie 'Descendants'"], ''Entertainment Weekly'', May 1, 2014; and Hurtado, Alexandra. [http://www.people.com/article/kristin-chenoweth-new-boyfriend-andrew-pruett "Kristin Chenoweth Steps Out with New Boyfriend in N.Y.C.: 'He's a Good Man,' She Tells ''People''"], ''People'' magazine, July 14, 2015</ref> It drew the largest cable TV movie audience of 2015 to that date.<ref>Kissell, Rick. [https://variety.com/2015/tv/ratings/descendants-ratings-disney-channel-1201554266/ "Disney Channel's 'Descendants' Bewitches 6.6 Million in Friday Premiere"], ''Variety'', August 1, 2015</ref> later that year, Chenoweth appeared in an episode of ''[[I Get That a Lot]]'', posing as a waitress,<ref>[http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/VIDEO-Sneak-Peek-Kristin-Chenoweth-Poses-As-Waitress-on-Tonights-I-GET-THAT-A-LOT-on-CBS-20151230 "Sneak Peek – Kristin Chenoweth Poses as Waitress on Tonight's ''I Get That a Lot'' on CBS"], BroadwayWorld.com, December 30, 2016</ref> and co-hosted the ''[[69th Tony Awards]]'', for which she was nominated for another Emmy Award.<ref>[http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2016/outstanding-special-class-programs "68th Emmy Awards Nominees and Winners: Outstanding Special Class Program – 2016"], Academy of Television Arts & Sciences, accessed June 19, 2017</ref> Chenoweth played Velma Von Tussle in NBC's ''[[Hairspray Live!]]'' in 2016.<ref name=Hairspray>Taylor Weatherby, Taylor. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7604497/kristin-chenoweth-miss-baltimore-crabs-hairspray-live-video "Watch Kristin Chenoweth Dominate ''Hairspray Live!'' With 'Miss Baltimore Crabs' Performance"], ''Billboard'', December 7, 2016</ref>

In 2017, Chenoweth played the role of [[Ēostre|Easter]] in the [[Starz]] TV series ''[[American Gods (TV series)|American Gods]]''<ref>Sava, Oliver. [https://www.vulture.com/2017/06/american-gods-season-1-finale-recap-come-to-jesus.html "American Gods Season Finale Recap: Don't Cross Easter"], Vulture.com, ''New York'' magazine, June 18, 2017</ref> and guested on ''[[Younger (TV series)|Younger]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/kristin-chenoweth-will-guest-star-on-youngers-season-4-premiere-find-out-who-shes-playing|title=Kristin Chenoweth Will Guest Star on ''Younger''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Season 4 Premiere; Find Out Who She's Playing|first=Ryan|last=McPhee|work=Playbill|date=May 31, 2017|access-date=May 31, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, a guest spot on ''[[Mom (TV series)|Mom]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tvinsider.com/657560/mom-kristin-chenoweth-guest-star |title='Mom' Stages Another 'West Wing' Reunion With Guest Star Kristin Chenoweth|first=Marisa|last=Roffman|work=TV Insider|date=January 9, 2018|access-date=January 24, 2018}}; and [https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Scoop-Coming-Up-On-All-New-MOM-on-CBS-Thursday-March-8-2018-20180214 "Scoop: Coming Up On All New MOM on CBS – Thursday, March 8, 2018"], February 14, 2018</ref> was followed by the main cast role, on ''[[Trial & Error (TV series)|Trial & Error]]'', of Lavinia Peck-Foster, an eccentric heiress accused of her husband's murder, who hires Josh Segal and Associates to defend her.<ref name=Best/><ref>Andreeva, Nellie and Denise Petski. [https://deadline.com/2018/02/kristin-chenoweth-star-nbc-trial-error-1202300044 "''Trial & Error'': Kristin Chenoweth to Star In Season 2 of NBC Legal Comedy Series"], ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'', February 22, 2018, accessed June 13, 2018</ref> She participated in a 2018 NBC broadcast, ''[[A Very Wicked Halloween]]'', hosting and singing ''Popular'' and other numbers to celebrate the 15th anniversary of ''Wicked'' on Broadway.<ref name=Lenker>Lenker, Maureen Lee. [https://ew.com/tv/2018/10/29/the-5-best-moments-in-a-very-wicked-halloween "The 5 best moments in ''A Very Wicked Halloween''], ''Entertainment Weekly'', October 29, 2018</ref> The same year, she appeared as a guest on another NBC special, ''[[Darci Lynne]]: My Hometown Christmas''.<ref>Darwish, Meaghan. [https://www.tvinsider.com/730541/darci-lynne-my-hometown-christmas-special-2018-nbc "'AGT' Winner Darci Lynne Invites Us to Cozy Up With ''My Hometown Christmas'' on NBC"], [[TV Insider]], November 12, 2018</ref> The next year, Chenoweth made another Christmas TV movie, ''A Christmas Love Story''.<ref>[https://www.hallmarkchannel.com/a-christmas-love-story ''A Christmas Love Story''], Hallmark, December 7, 2019</ref> The same year, she appeared on British TV as a judge on an ITV special "All Star Musicals", where she and [[Elaine Paige]] performed the song "[[I Know Him So Well]]" together.<ref>Duke, Simon. [https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/tv/all-star-musicals-elaine-kristin-15987531 "Watch All Star Musicals' Elaine Paige and Kristin Chenoweth's amazing duet of 'I Know Him So Well'"], ''ChronicleLive'', March 17, 2019</ref>

Chenoweth hosted a six-episode [[Food Network]] television competition show, derived from the game ''[[Candy Land]]'', in 2020–2021.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pomranz |first1=Mike |title=A ''Candy Land'' Competition Show Is Coming to Food Network |url=https://www.foodandwine.com/news/food-network-candy-land-show-kristin-chenoweth |publisher=Food and Wine |access-date=November 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ryan |first1=Patrick |title=Kristin Chenoweth heads to 'Candy Land' in Food Network's board game-inspired baking show |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2020/10/13/kristin-chenoweth-candy-land-food-network-baking-competition-tv-exclusive/5968543002/ |newspaper=USA Today |access-date=November 11, 2020}}</ref> In 2021, PBS aired a ''Wicked'' concert special, hosted by Chenoweth and Menzel, with "a starry line-up" of singers and actors performing the musical numbers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2021/08/wicked-in-concert-kristin-chenoweth-idina-menzel-pbs-full-cast-announced-1234809661/|title = Kristin Chenoweth & Idina Menzel to Host 'Wicked in Concert' PBS Special; Full Cast Announced|date = August 5, 2021}}</ref> She also appeared as the villainous Mildred Layton in the [[Apple TV+]] parody musical comedy television series ''[[Schmigadoon!]]''<ref name=Best/><ref name=Jacobs>Jacobs, Matthew. [https://www.townandcountrymag.com/leisure/arts-and-culture/a36972236/schmigadoon-kristin-chenoweth-interview "For ''Schmigadoon!'' Star Kristin Chenoweth, Nothing's As Good as Playing Bad"], ''[[Town & Country (magazine)|Town and Country]]'', July 16, 2021</ref> for which she was nominated for the 2022 [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]].<ref>Pedersen, Eric. [https://deadline.com/2021/12/critics-choice-awards-tv-nominations-2021-succession-hbo-netflix-1234885460 "Critics Choice TV Nominations: ''Succession'' Leads Field as HBO Edges Netflix"], [[Deadline Hollywood]], December 6, 2022. accessed December 7, 2021</ref> and a [[Hollywood Critics Association TV Awards|Hollywood Critics Association TV Award]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Verhoeven |first=Beatrice |date=July 7, 2022 |title='This Is Us,' 'Succession', 'Severance' Lead 2022 HCA TV Nominations |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/2022-hollywood-critics-association-broadcast-cable-tv-nominations-1235176458/ |access-date=July 8, 2022 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |archive-date=July 7, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220707225346/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/2022-hollywood-critics-association-broadcast-cable-tv-nominations-1235176458/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Later that year, she joined [[The Voice (American season 21)|''The Voice'', season 21]] as advisor to [[Ariana Grande]]'s team.<ref name=Bergeson>Bergeson, Samantha. [https://www.eonline.com/news/1299034/see-kristin-chenoweth-gush-over-joining-the-voice-with-coach-ariana-grande "See Kristin Chenoweth Gush Over Joining The Voice With Coach Ariana Grande"], EOnline, August 16, 2021</ref> She returned in 2023 for season 2 of ''Schmigadoon!'', this time as Miss Codwell, owner of an orphanage, receiving another Hollywood Critics Association TV Award nomination.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://awardswatch.com/the-boys-yellowjackets-abbott-elementary-lead-2023-hca-tv-awards-nominations/ |title='The Boys,' 'Yellowjackets,' 'Abbott Elementary' lead 2023 HCA TV Awards nominations |last=Anderson |first=Erik |work=AwardsWatch |date=July 11, 2023 |access-date=July 11, 2023}}</ref>

===Film===
Chenoweth made her theatrical film debut in ''Topa Topa Bluffs'' in 2002 playing "Patty".<ref>Marill, p. 161</ref> After a few years away from film, she returned to the big screen in the 2005 film version of ''[[Bewitched (2005 film)|Bewitched]]'', directed by [[Nora Ephron]], as Maria Kelly. In 2006, Chenoweth played supporting roles in five films, ''[[The Pink Panther (2006 film)|The Pink Panther]]'', ''[[RV (film)|RV]]'',<ref name=Best/> ''[[Running with Scissors (film)|Running with Scissors]]'', ''[[Deck the Halls (2006 film)|Deck the Halls]]''<ref name=Best/> and ''[[Stranger than Fiction (2006 film)|Stranger Than Fiction]]''. On February 24, 2008, Chenoweth sang "[[That's How You Know (musical number)|That's How You Know]]" from the film ''[[Enchanted (2007 film)|Enchanted]]'' at the [[80th Academy Awards]] in the [[Kodak Theatre]].<ref>[http://www.altfg.com/blog/movie/kristin-chenoweth-performs-thats-how-you-know/ "Kristin Chenoweth Performs 'That's How You Know': Oscar 2008"]. Alt Film Guide, 2008, accessed January 5, 2011</ref> In animated films, she voiced "a little charmer" called Kilowatt in ''[[Space Chimps]]''<ref>[[Roger Ebert|Ebert, Roger]]. [https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/space-chimps-2008 "Three apes in a worm hole"], RogerEbert.com, July 17, 2008</ref> and another role, Rosetta the garden fairy, in ''[[Tinker Bell (film)|Tinker Bell]]'' (both 2008).<ref name=NPR2009/> She also appeared in the 2008 holiday [[romantic comedy]] ''[[Four Christmases]]'', playing the sister of [[Reese Witherspoon]]'s character.

In 2009, Chenoweth starred as a "suicidal prostitute" in the indie drama ''[[Into Temptation (film)|Into Temptation]]'', written and directed by Patrick Coyle. The film was screened at the [[Newport Beach Film Festival]] and was later released on DVD.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i9808673cbfb6ec1f7610fb16dd00c5fc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616213717/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i9808673cbfb6ec1f7610fb16dd00c5fc |archive-date=June 16, 2008 | title=Kristin Chenoweth lured to "Temptation"|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] }}</ref> Also in 2009, Chenoweth reprised her voice role of Rosetta in ''[[Tinker Bell and the Lost Treasure]]'' and ''[[Tinker Bell and the Great Fairy Rescue]]'', and filmed the Disney comedy ''[[You Again]]'' (released in 2010). She was called "memorable" in the supporting role of Debra in the 2012 action comedy ''[[Hit and Run (2012 film)|Hit and Run]]''.<ref name=Best/> She played Samatha in ''[[Family Weekend]]'' (2013).<ref name=Best/><ref>Abrams, Rachel. [https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118030320 "Chenoweth, Modine join ''Family''"], ''Variety'', January 15, 2011, accessed April 24, 2016</ref> Chenoweth next voiced Gabi, a poisonous frog, in the 2014 animated film, ''[[Rio 2]]'',<ref>[https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Rio-2-Adds-Bruno-Mars-Kristin-Chenoweth-Voice-Cast-35942.html Rio 2 Adds Bruno Mars, Kristin Chenoweth To Voice Cast], Cinemablend.com, accessed February 24, 2013</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2013/09/24/rio-2-first-look/2829083/|title=First Look: Rio 2|first=Bryan|last=Alexander|work=USA Today|date=September 24, 2013|access-date=October 3, 2013}}</ref> and starred as Mrs. Kemp in ''[[The Opposite Sex (2014 film)|The Opposite Sex]]'' (2014).<ref>[https://www.tvguide.com/movies/the-opposite-sex/cast/2030109488 "''The Opposite Sex'' – Full Cast & Crew"], ''TV Guide'', accessed April 24, 2024</ref>

In 2015, she appeared in the thriller ''[[The Boy Next Door (film)|The Boy Next Door]]'' and voiced the Sugar Plum Fairy in ''[[Strange Magic (film)|Strange Magic]]''<ref>Gioia, Michael. [https://playbill.com/article/strange-magic-film-inspired-by-midsummer-and-with-voices-of-alan-cumming-and-kristin-chenoweth-released-com-339888 ""Strange Magic" Film, Inspired by ''Midsummer'' and With Voices of Alan Cumming and Kristin Chenoweth, Released"], ''Playbill'', January 23, 2015</ref> and [[Fifi (Peanuts)|Fifi]], [[Snoopy]]'s love interest, in ''[[The Peanuts Movie]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/84814/boy-next-door-opens-image-gallery-new-clips/|title=The Boy Next Door |work=BD|date=September 24, 2013|access-date=October 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2015/10/28/kristin-chenoweth-voices-fifi-from-peanuts-snoopy-lover/74712518/|title=Exclusive: Chenoweth voices Snoopy's love Fifi|first=Bryan|last=Alexander| work=USA Today|date=October 28, 2015|access-date=October 29, 2015}}</ref> The next year she played Lorna Buchanan in ''[[Hard Sell (film)|Hard Sell]]''.<ref name=Best/><ref>Scheck, Frank. [https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movies/movie-reviews/hard-sell-film-review-896083/ "''Hard Sell'': Film Review], ''The Hollywood Reporter'', May 20, 2016</ref> In 2017, she played Janet Krauss in ''[[Class Rank (film)|Class Rank]]'' and voiced Princess Skystar in the 2017 animated ''[[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|My Little Pony: The Movie]]'',<ref>Russian, Ale. [http://people.com/movies/my-little-pony-movie-first-look-360-image Ale "Dive Into ''My Little Pony: The Movie's'' Colorful Underwater World in This Exclusive First Look"], ''People'' magazine, May 22, 2017, accessed July 14, 2017</ref> and Abby the Mouse in ''[[The Star (2017 film)|The Star]]''.<ref name="The Star">{{cite web|title=Sony Animation Announces Details & Release Date for Lin-Manuel Miranda's VIVO| url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Sony-Animation-Announces-Details-Release-Date-for-Lin-Manuel-Mirandas-VIVO-20170118| website=BroadwayWorld|date=January 18, 2017|access-date=January 19, 2017}}</ref> Chenoweth headlined the [[Hallmark Channel|Hallmark Channel’s]] 2019 Countdown to Christmas with film ''A Christmas Love Story''.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bentley |first=Jean |date=2019-07-26 |title=Kristin Chenoweth to Headline Hallmark Channel's 2019 Countdown to Christmas (Exclusive) |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/hallmark-channel-adds-11-movies-2019-countdown-christmas-1227350/ |access-date=2024-08-27 |website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> She voiced another mouse, Daisy, in ''[[The Witches (2020 film)|The Witches]]'' (2020)<ref>Tisdale, Jerrica. [https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2557712/the-witches-differences-between-the-anne-hathaway-movie-and-the-roald-dahl-book "''The Witches'': 9 Differences Between the Anne Hathaway Movie and the Roald Dahl Book"], ''Cinema Blend'', October 28, 2020</ref> and played Bailey in ''[[National Champions (film)|National Champions]]'' (2021).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2021/05/national-champions-kristin-chenoweth-jeffrey-donovan-lil-rel-howery-stx-sports-drama-1234760204/|title='National Champions': Kristin Chenoweth, Jeffrey Donovan & Lil Rel Howery Board STX Sports Drama|date=May 19, 2021|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210519171701/https://deadline.com/2021/05/national-champions-kristin-chenoweth-jeffrey-donovan-lil-rel-howery-stx-sports-drama-1234760204/|archive-date=May 19, 2021|url-status=live|access-date=May 19, 2021}}</ref> She was Aunt Susan in ''[[Holidate]]'' (2020)<ref>{{Cite web |last=N'Duka |first=Amanda |date=2019-05-14 |title=Luke Bracey, Jessica Capshaw, Frances Fisher, Jake Manley, Kristin Chenoweth & More Join Emma Roberts In ''Holidate'' Film At Netflix |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/luke-bracey-jessica-capshaw-frances-fisher-jake-manley-kristin-chenoweth-emma-roberts-holidate-netflix-1202614603/ |access-date=2024-08-27 |website=Deadline}}</ref> and had a cameo in the 2022 film [[Bros (film)|''Bros'']] as herself.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Billy Eichner reveals why those hilarious A-list cameos happen at the end of 'Bros' |url=https://ew.com/movies/billy-eichner-reveals-why-hilarious-a-list-cameos-happen-at-end-of-bros/ |access-date=2024-08-27 |website=EW.com}}</ref> Chenoweth and [[Lindsay Lohan]] are set to star in the romantic comedy ''[[Our Little Secret (film)|Our Little Secret]]'' on [[Netflix]], scheduled for release in November 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rubin |first=Rebecca |date=2024-01-22 |title=Lindsay Lohan and Kristin Chenoweth to Star in Netflix Rom-Com ''Our Little Secret'' |url=https://variety.com/2024/film/news/lindsay-lohan-kristin-chenoweth-netflix-our-little-secret-1235881304/ |access-date=2024-08-27 |website=Variety}}</ref>  

===Other media===
Chenoweth often appeared on ''[[A Prairie Home Companion]]''.<ref>[http://find.publicradio.org/search?site=phc&proxystylesheet=phc&filter=p&access=p&output=xml_no_dtd&q=chenoweth&x=0&y=0 Links to Chenoweth's appearances on ''Prairie Home Companion'']{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}, accessed January 2, 2011.</ref> On August 27, 2008, Chenoweth released an internet video with [[Funny or Die]] called ''Intervention with Kristin Chenoweth''.<ref name="funny or die">{{cite web| url=http://www.funnyordie.com/videos/aa15baae2b| title=Intervention with Kristin Chenoweth| work=funnyordie.com| access-date=August 27, 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024005428/http://www.funnyordie.com/videos/aa15baae2b| archive-date=October 24, 2008| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref> The video parodied [[A&E (TV network)|A&E]]'s show ''[[Intervention (TV series)|Intervention]]'', with Chenoweth starring as a singing, dancing interventionist. The song in the video was composed by [[Andrew Lippa]], with lyrics by Amy Rhodes, who also wrote the script for the video.<ref name="funny or die"/> Chenoweth admitted that she was hesitant about performing the lyrics.<ref>Malkin, Marc. [http://www.eonline.com/news/26516/kristin-chenoweth-reveals-her-crystal-method "Kristin Chenoweth Reveals Her Crystal Method"], Eonline.com, August 28, 2008, accessed February 12, 2017</ref>

In 2010, she appeared in a three-minute video short for ''[[Glamour Magazine]]'' titled "iPad or Bust".<ref>[http://cargocollective.com/jennyryanbowman/filter/writing/iPad-or-Bust-feat-Kristin-Chenoweth "'iPad or Bust' feat. Kristin Chenoweth"]{{Dead link|date=October 2022 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, CargoCollective.com, 2010, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> She posed for the cover and a photo spread in the March 2006 edition of ''[[FHM]]'' magazine.<ref>''FHM Magazine'', March 2006, Issue 65</ref> In 2011, Chenoweth released her first televised music video on [[Country Music Television]], directed by [[Roman White]], for her song "[[I Want Somebody (Bitch About)|I Want Somebody]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/videos/kristin-chenoweth/660013/i-want-somebody.jhtml|title=Kristin Chenoweth: I want somebody|website=CMT|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110630145104/http://www.cmt.com/videos/kristin-chenoweth/660013/i-want-somebody.jhtml|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 30, 2011|publisher=MTV Networks| access-date=February 12, 2017}}</ref> The video for the single peaked at #19 on [[Country Music Television|CMT]]'s Top 20 Countdown.<ref>{{cite web|title=CMT Top 20 Countdown|publisher=[[Country Music Television]]|access-date=June 28, 2011|year=2011|url=http://www.cmt.com/shows/dyn/top_twenty_countdown/series_wildcard.jhtml?wildcard=/dynamic_templates/shows/center_templates/wildcard/top_twenty_countdown//countdown_070111_main.jhtml&event_id=895632|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605195712/http://www.cmt.com/shows/dyn/top_twenty_countdown/series_wildcard.jhtml?wildcard=/dynamic_templates/shows/center_templates/wildcard/top_twenty_countdown//countdown_070111_main.jhtml&event_id=895632|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 5, 2013}}</ref>

In 2022, Chenoweth dipped into journalism in the mini-series ''Keeper of the Ashes: The Oklahoma Girl Scout Murders'' on [[Hulu]]. In the special, she investigates the [[Oklahoma Girl Scout Murders|1977 murders of three girls]] at a [[Girl Scouts of the USA|Girl Scout]] camp that the young Chenoweth had been unable to attend that year due to illness.<ref name=ashes>{{cite web | last=Yamada |first=Haley| title=The Oklahoma Girl Scout murders hit home for actress Kristin Chenoweth | website=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] | date=May 25, 2022 | url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/oklahoma-girl-scout-murders-hit-home-actress-kristin/story?id=84832217 | access-date=November 5, 2022}}</ref> The same year, she published her first picture book, ''What Will I Do for My Love Today?''<ref>{{Cite web |last=Conway |first=Jeff |title=Kristin Chenoweth on Her New Children's Book, Finding Love, and Her Confidence in the Upcoming ''Wicked'' Films |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffconway/2022/03/08/kristin-chenoweth-on-her-new-childrens-book-finding-love-and-her-confidence-in-the-upcoming-wicked-film/ |access-date=2024-08-27 |website=Forbes}}</ref> 

===Recordings and concerts===
[[File:Kristin Chenoweth.jpg|thumb|left|Chenoweth in 2008]]
Chenoweth has a distinctive speaking voice, one she has compared to that of [[Betty Boop]].<ref>Scott, Walter. [http://parade.com/275926/walterscott/youll-get-to-hear-kristin-chenoweths-voice-in-rio-2/ "Kristin Chenoweth Takes a Wicked Vocal Turn in ''Rio 2''"], ''Parade'' magazine, April 5, 2014, accessed September 22, 2015</ref> She is a classically trained [[coloratura soprano]], able to sing the note "F6" (also known as "F above High C").<ref>Manus, Willard. [http://www.playbill.com/article/kristin-chenoweth-goes-coast-to-coast-com-101516 "Kristin Chenoweth Goes Coast to Coast"], ''Playbill'', June 5, 2001, accessed February 12, 2017</ref>

Among other early recordings, Chenoweth participated in a studio cast recording of ''[[The Most Happy Fella]]'' in 1992. She was also in the cast recordings of ''A New Brain'' (1998) and ''You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'' (1999) and a studio cast recording of ''[[110 in the Shade]]'' (1999). In 2000, she was featured on the album ''Grateful: The Songs of [[John Bucchino]]''. The next year, with Mandy Patinkin, she was featured on the album titled "Kidults".<ref name=Kristinofficial/> Also in 2001, she released her debut solo album ''[[Let Yourself Go (Kristin Chenoweth album)|Let Yourself Go]]'', which was a collection of standards from the musicals of the 1930s. One of the tracks featured a duet with [[Jason Alexander]]. In {{Nowrap|October 2002}}, Chenoweth performed songs from the album in concert for [[Lincoln Center]]'s American Songbook concert series.<ref>Holden, Stephen. [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/14/arts/pop-review-a-glamorous-chameleon-catching-all-the-nuances.html "A Glamorous Chameleon, Catching All the Nuances"]. ''The New York Times'', {{Nowrap|October 14}}, 2002</ref> Ben Rimalower, in ''Playbill'', praised the album as "a joyous affair".<ref name=Rimalower/> The same year, she appeared as [[Fanny Brice]] in the Actor's Fund Benefit Concert of the musical ''[[Funny Girl (musical)|Funny Girl]]'' in New York City. In 2003 in London, she performed a solo concert as part of the ''[[Divas at the Donmar]]'' series for director [[Sam Mendes]].  Later that year, she sang Glinda in the cast recording of ''Wicked'' and the soundtrack recording of Disney's ''The Music Man''. Rimalower wrote that Chenoweth "sparkles" on the album.<ref name=Rimalower/> In 2004, she released her second album ''[[As I Am (Kristin Chenoweth album)|As I Am]]'', which was a Christian music album containing various spiritual songs. The album peaked at number 31 on the U.S. Christian Albums Chart. The same year, Chenoweth gave [[Kristin Chenoweth at Carnegie Hall|a concert at Carnegie Hall]].<ref name=Kristinofficial/>

On January 19, 2007, Chenoweth performed a solo concert at [[The Metropolitan Opera]] in New York titled [[Kristin Chenoweth Live At The Met]], making history as only the third musical theatre star ever to present a solo concert at that location, following [[Barbara Cook]] and [[Yves Montand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metoperafamily.org/metopera/season/production.aspx?id=9186|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213121741/http://www.metoperafamily.org/metopera/season/production.aspx?id=9186|date=February 13, 2008|archive-date=February 13, 2008|title=Kristin Chenoweth: Live at the Met |access-date=May 22, 2007}}</ref> The same year, she was featured in songs with [[Nathan Gunn]] on an album titled ''Just Before Sunrise''. The next year, she released her third solo studio album, titled ''[[A Lovely Way to Spend Christmas]]''. The album included a duet with [[John Pizzarelli]], and there are several modern holiday tunes, but many traditional carols as well, including ''[[The Lord's Prayer]]''. This album has been her best-seller, reaching number 77 on the U.S. Billboard Albums Chart, number 7 on the U.S. Holiday Albums chart and number 1 on the U.S. Heatseekers chart. Ben Rimalower, in ''Playbill'', observed that the album "proved an ideal showcase for [Chenoweth's] many gifts".<ref name=Rimalower/> Among many other solo concerts around the U.S., Chenoweth performed her own concert in 2009 with the [[St. Louis Symphony Orchestra]] at the [[Fox Theatre (St. Louis, Missouri)|Fox Theatre]].<ref>[http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Kristin_Chenoweth_Appears_with_St_Louis_Symphony_Orchestra_at_Fox_Theatre_Jan_10_20090106 "Kristin Chenoweth Appears with St. Louis Symphony Orchestra at Fox Theatre Jan. 10"]. BroadwayWorld.com, {{Nowrap|January 6}}, 2009, accessed {{Nowrap|May 12}}, 2010</ref>

In August 2010, during her nights off from ''Promises, Promises'', Chenoweth recorded her fourth album, a [[country pop|country-pop]] CD titled ''[[Some Lessons Learned]]''.<ref>[http://www.autostraddle.com/kristin-chenoweth-interview-54113/ Kristin Chenoweth is Popular and Possibly Perfect: The Auto-Interview]. ''AutoStraddle'', {{Nowrap|July 30}}, 2010</ref> Released on September 13, 2011, the album contains songs by [[Diane Warren]], [[Dolly Parton]] and [[Lady Antebellum]]'s [[Hillary Scott]], among others. Chenoweth co-wrote two of the songs.<ref>Derschowitz, Jessica. [https://www.cbsnews.com/news/kristin-chenoweth-goes-country-with-some-lessons-learned/ "Kristin Chenoweth goes country with ''Some Lessons Learned''"], CBS, September 14, 2011</ref><ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic| class=album| id=r2250589| pure_url=yes}}|title=''Some Lessons Learned'' review|last=O'Brien|first=Jon|work=[[Allmusic]]| access-date=September 14, 2011}}</ref> In advance of the album, Chenoweth released the song "[[I Want Somebody (Bitch About)]]".<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/scene/tv/kristin-chenoweth-to-release-country-album-star-in-new-tv/article_ff0e80f3-2eae-56c3-ac88-cd3595248a06.html| title=Kristin Chenoweth to release country album, star in new TV series| last=Sherrow| first=Rita| date=May 18, 2011|work=Tulsa World|access-date=February 12, 2017}}</ref> Ben Rimalower, writing in ''Playbill'', thought that the album "may be Chenoweth's most accomplished".<ref name=Rimalower/> From the TV show ''GCB'', in 2012, Chenoweth released "Blessed Be the Ties that Bind",<ref>[https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/blessed-be-ties-that-bind/id505708545 "Blessed Be the Ties that Bind"], iTunes, accessed April 19, 2012</ref> "[[Jesus Take the Wheel]]",<ref>[https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/jesus-take-the-wheel-single/id511339874 "Jesus Take the Wheel – Single"], iTunes, accessed April 19, 2012</ref> "[[Make Me an Instrument of Your Peace|Prayer of St. Francis]]" (which was also on ''Some Lessons Learned'')<ref>[https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/prayer-of-st.-francis-single/id517306693 "Prayer of St. Francis – Single"], iTunes, accessed April 19, 2012</ref> and "[[This Little Light of Mine]]".<ref>[https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/this-little-light-mine-single/id516994759 "This Little Light of Mine – Single"], iTunes, accessed April 19, 2012</ref> Chenoweth conducted her first [[Kristin Chenoweth In Concert|U.S. concert tour]] in the summer of 2012. The reviewer for BroadwayWorld.com wrote: "Kristin shines on stage."<ref>Irwin, Jay. [http://seattle.broadwayworld.com/article/Review-Kristin-Chenoweth-in-Concert-at-the-Paramount-Theatre-20120510 "Review: Kristin Chenoweth in Concert at the Paramount Theatre"], BroadwayWorld.com,  May 10, 2012, accessed October 20, 2012</ref>

Less than four months after her July 2012 injury on the set of ''The Good Wife'', Chenoweth returned to the concert stage for a short series of dates in California, where she performed "a sagely programmed 90-minute set, which merged pop, Broadway, gospel and country with perky, unforced-feeling remarks. Chenoweth's range, timbre and versatility are in peak form, with astonishing top notes, equalized registers and a delicious ability to variegate attack from number to number."<ref name=fracture>Nichols, David C. [https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-kristin-chenoweth-review-segerstrom-20121106,0,2795590.story "Review: Kristin Chenoweth in top form at Segerstrom Concert Hall"], ''Los Angeles Times'', November 6, 2012</ref> In 2013, Chenoweth performed at the [[Sydney Opera House]] as part of an Australian concert tour.<ref>Allen, David. [http://aussietheatre.com.au/reviews/kristin-chenoweth-at-sydney-opera-house "Kristin Chenoweth at Sydney Opera House"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402125144/http://aussietheatre.com.au/reviews/kristin-chenoweth-at-sydney-opera-house |date=April 2, 2015 }}, AussieTheatre.com, June 19, 2013, accessed February 28, 2015</ref> In 2014, Chenoweth returned to Carnegie Hall with an autobiographical concert, ''[[The Evolution of a Soprano]]'', where she sang "as good a rendition of 'Much More' as we're ever likely to hear".<ref name=Carnegie2014/> She also made her London solo concert debut at the [[Royal Albert Hall]], where a reviewer's five-star review noted: "Chenoweth undeniably knows how to engulf a venue, not only with her (sometimes surprisingly) powerful, operatic voice but also with her irresistible personality that audience was in the palm of her hands for the duration of the evening".<ref>Millward, Tom. [https://www.londontheatre.co.uk/theatre-news/news/review-of-an-evening-with-kristin-chenoweth "Review of ''An Evening with Kristin Chenoweth''"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023120047/https://www.londontheatre.co.uk/theatre-news/news/review-of-an-evening-with-kristin-chenoweth |date=October 23, 2018 }}, ''London Theatre Guide'', July 13, 2014</ref> She joined [[Andrew Lippa]] in his [[oratorio]] ''I Am [[Harvey Milk]]'' at [[Avery Fisher Hall]] on October 6, 2014.<ref>Hetrick, Adam. [https://www.playbill.com/article/i-am-harvey-milk-with-kristin-chenoweth-and-andrew-lippa-premieres-in-new-york-com-332141 "''I Am Harvey Milk'', with Kristin Chenoweth and Andrew Lippa, Premieres in New York"], ''Playbill'', October 6, 2014</ref>

In 2014, Chenoweth released an album titled ''[[Coming Home (Kristin Chenoweth album)|Coming Home]]''.<ref name=ComingHome>Watts, James D. Jr. [http://www.tulsaworld.com/scene/artsandentertainment/review-kristin-chenoweth-coming-home/article_7d56a9a2-11ca-58f7-879f-b69199cbb6fe.html "Kristin Chenoweth: Coming Home"], TulsaWorld.com, August 23, 2014, accessed June 2, 2015</ref> The album charted at No. 48 on the Billboard 200 chart.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/artist/306108/kristin-chenoweth/chart Kristen Chenoweth chart history], Billboard.com, accessed December 2, 2014</ref> Her [[Coming Home Tour]] continued into 2017.<ref>Kennedy, Marina. [http://www.broadwayworld.com/los-angeles/article/KRISTEN-CHENOWETH-Teams-with-IfOnly-to-Benefit-ACLU-of-Southern-California-20160610 "Kristin Chenoweth Teams with IfOnly to Benefit ACLU of Southern California"], BroadwayWorld.com, June 10, 2016</ref> Chenoweth released her next album, ''[[The Art of Elegance]]'', in 2016,<ref>[http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Kristin-Chenoweth-to-Release-New-Album-The-Art-of-Elegance-September-23-20160804 "Kristin Chenoweth to Release New Album ''The Art of Elegance'' September 23"], BroadwayWorld.com, accessed August 6, 2016</ref> which debuted at No. 36 on the ''Billboard 200''<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/2016-10-15 ''Billboard 200''], Billboard.com, accessed October 4, 2016</ref> and No. 1 on the Billboard Jazz Albums chart.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/charts/jazz-albums/2016-10-15 "Jazz Albums"], Billboard, October 15, 2016</ref> One of the songs on the album, "[[I'm a Fool to Want You]]", was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for its arrangements.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597556/grammys-nominees-complete-list-2017 "Here Is the Complete List of Nominees for the 2017 Grammys"], ''Billboard'', December 6, 2016</ref> She gave a series of concerts at Broadway's [[Lunt-Fontanne Theatre]], titled ''[[Kristin Chenoweth: My Love Letter to Broadway|My Love Letter to Broadway]]'', in 2016.<ref>Lloyd Webber, Imogen. [http://www.broadway.com/buzz/185841/tony-winner-kristin-chenoweth-to-return-to-the-great-white-way-in-my-love-letter-to-broadway "Tony Winner Kristin Chenoweth to Return to the Great White Way] in ''[[My Love Letter to Broadway]]'', Broadway.com, September 6, 2016</ref> In 2017, she gave a concert at the [[London Palladium]], where she "put on a spectacular show and simultaneously formed a heartfelt connection with her fans."<ref>Swain, Marianka. [https://www.broadwayworld.com/westend/article/BWW-Review-AN-INTIMATE-EVENING-WITH-KRISTIN-CHENOWETH-London-Palladium-20171021 "BWW Review: ''An Intimate Evening with Kristin Chenoweth'', London Palladium"], BroadwayWorld.com, October 21, 2017</ref>

Chenoweth released the album ''[[For the Girls]]'' on September 27, 2019, which features covers of songs by female performers from various genres that have influenced her. She collaborated with [[Dolly Parton]], [[Reba McEntire]], [[Jennifer Hudson]] and [[Ariana Grande]] on the album.<ref>King, Eric. [https://www.broadway.com/buzz/196591/kristin-chenoweths-new-album-will-feature-ariana-grande-jennifer-hudson-dolly-parton-reba-mcentire "Kristin Chenoweth's New Album Will Feature Ariana Grande, Jennifer Hudson, Dolly Parton & Reba McEntire"], Broadway.com, August 8, 2019</ref> In support of the album, she presented a concert series titled ''[[Kristin Chenoweth: For the Girls]]'' at the [[Nederlander Theatre]] from November 8 to 17, 2019.<ref name="For the Girls">[https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Kristin-Chenoweth-Will-Bring-FOR-THE-GIRLS-Solo-Show-to-Broadway-This-Fall-20190917 "Kristin Chenoweth Will Bring ''For the Girls'' Solo Show to Broadway This Fall!"], BroadwayWorld.com, September 17, 2019</ref> She released a second holiday album, ''Happiness Is Christmas'', in October 2021,<ref>Wild, Stephi. [https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/LISTEN-Kristin-Chenoweth-Announces-Happiness-Is-Christmas-Album-Listen-to-the-First-Song-Now-20210904 "Listen: Kristin Chenoweth Announces ''Happiness Is Christmas'' Album; Listen to the First Song Now!"], BroadwayWorld.com, September 4, 2021</ref> and returned to the Metropolitan Opera House with a new program, ''[[Christmas at the Met]]'', on December 13, 2021, to promote the album.<ref>Mosher, Stephen. [https://www.broadwayworld.com/cabaret/article/BWW-Review-Kristin-Chenoweth-Wins-Christmas-With-CHRISTMAS-AT-THE-MET-at-The-Metropolitan-Opera-20211214 "BWW Review: Kristin Chenoweth Wins Christmas with ''Christmas at the Met'' at The Metropolitan Opera"], December 14, 2021</ref>

==Special events and appearances==
Chenoweth and the cast of the Broadway musical ''Wicked'' performed the song "One Short Day" in the 2003 [[Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade]].<ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/article/wicked-and-boy-from-oz-featured-on-macys-thanksgiving-day-parade-com-116122 "''Wicked'' and ''Boy From Oz'' Featured on Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade"], Playbill, November 3, 2003, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> In the 2005 Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade, Chenoweth performed the song "Oklahoma" while riding aboard the "Oklahoma Rising" float. The float was making the first of three annual appearances commemorating the state of Oklahoma's statehood centennial in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://okc.about.com/od/attractionsandevents/a/oklahomamacy.htm|title=Oklahoma in the Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade|work=About.com|access-date=December 8, 2008|archive-date=September 22, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150922210127/http://okc.about.com/od/attractionsandevents/a/oklahomamacy.htm|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ok.gov/newsroom.php?page_id=4936&type=1|title=OK Centennial to be Featured in Thanksgiving Macy's Parade |work=State of Oklahoma press release|date=November 18, 2006}}</ref> She was the star performer of the opening ceremony of the 2007 Tournament of Roses Parade. She sang "Our Good Nature", an original composition written to coincide with the Oklahoma centennial celebration and the theme of the parade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ok.gov/newsroom.php?page_id=4985&type=1 |title=Oklahoma|website=Ok.gov|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> In the 2008 Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade, she performed the song "The Christmas Waltz" from her "A Lovely Way to Spend Christmas" album while riding aboard the "Care Bears Winter Fun-Derland" float.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.macys.com/campaign/parade/parade.jsp |title=Macy's |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202042916/http://www1.macys.com/campaign/parade/parade.jsp |archive-date=December 2, 2008 }}</ref>

She sang with [[Il Divo]] as part of Il Divo's Christmas Tour on {{Nowrap|December 15}}, 16 and 17, 2009, in New York City and {{Nowrap|December 18}} in Boston.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Exclusive_Performance_Coverage_Il_Divo_Kristin_Chenoweth_Holiday_Concert_20091217|title=Exclusive Performance Coverage: Il Divo & Kristin Chenoweth Holiday Concert|website=Broadwayworld.com|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/ae/music/articles/2009/12/17/kristin_chenoweth_discusses_her_career_and_her_tour_with_il_divo| title=Things are working out|work=The Boston Globe|first=Hayley|last=Kaufman|date=December 17, 2009}}</ref> She has sung the [[The Star-Spangled Banner|U.S. national anthem]] at various sporting events, including the 2010 [[New York Yankees]] home opener,<ref>[http://broadwayworld.com/article/Chenoweth_Opens_NY_Yankee_Game_with_National_Anthem_413_20100412 "Chenoweth Opens NY Yankee Game with National Anthem, 4/13"], BroadwayWorld, April 12, 2010, accessed January 22, 2012</ref> at [[Candlestick Park]] for the [[NFL]]'s [[2011–12 NFL playoffs|NFC Conference Championship]] on January 22, 2012,<ref>[http://www.broadway.com/buzz/159526/watch-kristin-chenoweth-sing-the-national-anthem-at-the-giants-vs-49ers-game "Watch Kristin Chenoweth Sing the National Anthem at the Giants vs. 49ers Game"], Broadway.com, January 23, 2012, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> at the [[Arizona Cardinals]]' season opener in 2016 and their game at [[University of Phoenix Stadium]] against the [[Seattle Seahawks]] on November 9, 2017.<ref>[http://www.12news.com/sports/nfl/cardinals/kristin-chenoweth-will-sing-at-luke-afb-cardinals-game-this-week/489715336 "Kristin Chenoweth will sing at Luke AFB, Cardinals game this week"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111050240/http://www.12news.com/sports/nfl/cardinals/kristin-chenoweth-will-sing-at-luke-afb-cardinals-game-this-week/489715336 |date=November 11, 2017 }}, [[KPNX]] TV, November 9, 2017</ref> Also in 2010, Chenoweth hosted the [[15th Critics' Choice Awards|15th Annual Broadcast Film Critics Association Awards]] on [[VH1]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://movies.broadwayworld.com/article/Kristin_Chenoweth_to_Host_15th_Annual_Critics_Choice_Movie_Awards_Broadcast_Jan_15_20091209| title=Kristin Chenoweth to Host 15th Annual Critics' Choice Movie Awards; Broadcast January 15|website=Movies.broadwayworld.com|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref>

In 2013, Chenoweth co-hosted the [[Oscars Red Carpet Live]] immediately prior to the [[85th Academy Awards]]<ref>[http://broadwayworld.com/article/Kristin-Chenoweth-to-Co-Host-Oscars-Pre-Show-224-20130214 "Kristin Chenoweth to Co-Host Oscars Pre-Show, 2/24"], BroadwayWorld.com, February 14, 2013, accessed April 24, 2016</ref> and also sang the closing number of the ceremony, "Here's to the Losers", with host [[Seth MacFarlane]], in which, paraphrasing the original [[Frank Sinatra]] song, the two poked genial fun at nominees who had not received awards.<ref>[https://www.cinemablend.com/new/kristin-chenoweth-seth-macfarlane-close-out-oscars-with-song-35903.html Kristin Chenoweth and Seth MacFarlane to Close Out the Oscars with a Song] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200803045335/https://www.cinemablend.com/new/kristin-chenoweth-seth-macfarlane-close-out-oscars-with-song-35903.html |date=August 3, 2020 }}. Cinemablend.com, accessed February 24, 2013</ref> Chenoweth was the solo performer in the [[Live from Lincoln Center]] feature "The Dames of Broadway... All of 'Em!!!"<ref name=Rimalower/> In July, she hosted the fifth [[Just For Laughs]] gala in Montreal.<ref>Brownstein, Bill. [https://montrealgazette.com/Kristin+Chenoweth+leads+Wicked+good+gala/8714680/story.html "Kristin Chenoweth leads Wicked good gala"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116163515/http://www.montrealgazette.com/Kristin+Chenoweth+leads+Wicked+good+gala/8714680/story.html |date=November 16, 2018 }}, the Montreal ''Gazette'', July 26, 2013</ref> She also appeared in the 2013 Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade performing the song "[[Theme from New York, New York|New York, New York]]" while riding aboard [[Royal Caribbean International|Royal Caribbean]]'s "A World at Sea" float.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://markets.on.nytimes.com/research/stocks/news/press_release.asp |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=A Magnificent Celebration: The 87th Annual Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade Kicks Off the Holiday Season }}; {{cite web|url=http://www.newyork.com/articles/travel/5-floats-to-look-out-for-at-macys-thanksgiving-day-parade-06209/ |work=newyork.com |title=5 Floats to Look Out for at Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202052546/http://www.newyork.com/articles/travel/5-floats-to-look-out-for-at-macys-thanksgiving-day-parade-06209/ |archive-date=December 2, 2013 }}; {{cite web|url=http://www.coolcruisenews.com/2013/11/28/behind-the-floats/ |work=coolcruisenews.com |title=Behind the Floats |date=November 28, 2013 }}</ref>

In 2015, she co-hosted the Tony Awards.<ref>Pesce, Niclole Lyn. [http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tony-awards-2015-top-5-kristin-chenoweth-alan-cumming-jokes-article-1.2250085 "Tony Awards 2015: Top 5 Kristin Chenoweth and Alan Cumming moments"], ''New York Daily News'', June 7, 2015</ref> She appeared as a guest with Andrea Bocelli on some of his 2017–2018 American tour stops.<ref>Janes, Théoden. [http://www.charlotteobserver.com/entertainment/music-news-reviews/article199470624.html "Concert review: Did Andrea Bocelli's first visit to Charlotte live up to the hype?"], ''The Charlotte Observer'', February 10, 2018; Viagas, Robert. [https://www.playbill.com/article/kristin-chenoweth-will-sing-with-andrea-bocelli-at-madison-square-garden "Kristin Chenoweth Will Sing With Andrea Bocelli at Madison Square Garden"], ''Playbill'', December 11, 2017</ref> In December 2018, Chenoweth performed with and narrated the [[Tabernacle Choir]]'s yearly Christmas concert series in [[Salt Lake City]], Utah.<ref>{{Cite news |date=December 14, 2018 |title=Kristin Chenoweth Dazzles in Christmas Concert with Tabernacle Choir |url=https://www.sltrib.com/artsliving/2018/12/14/kristin-chenoweth-dazzles |newspaper=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]}}</ref>

==Personal life==
[[File:Kristin Chenoweth, Yankees Home Opener 2010.jpg|right|thumb|Chenoweth sang the U.S. national anthem for the [[New York Yankees|Yankees]]' home opener in 2010.]]
In 2009, Chenoweth published a memoir, ''[[A Little Bit Wicked|A Little Bit Wicked: Life, Love, and Faith in Stages]]'', describing her life and career, including her adoption, her turn in ''Wicked'' and her time in Hollywood.<ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/article/chenoweths-autobiography-a-little-bit-wicked-due-in-april-2009-com-151386 "Chenoweth's Autobiography, ''A Little Bit Wicked'', Due in April&nbsp; 2009"], ''Playbill'', July 3, 2008, accessed February 12, 2017</ref> Chenoweth suffers from [[Ménière's disease]], an inner-ear disorder that can cause vertigo, headaches and nausea, among other symptoms. She has said that during some performances, she leaned on her co-stars to keep her balance, and that it has caused her to miss performances.<ref name=NPR2009/>

Chenoweth has spoken publicly about her religious faith; she describes herself as a "non-judgmental, [[Liberal Christianity|liberal Christian]]".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/10/fashion/10nite.html| work=The New York Times|title=Fashion & Style "A Night Out With: Kristin Chenoweth: Head Shots"| first=Pauline|last=O'Connor|date=April 10, 2005|access-date=May 7, 2010}}</ref> According to ''The New York Times'', when Chenoweth "assured her theater fans that she supports gay rights, her Christian base was outraged; she was disinvited from performing at a Women of Faith conference in {{Nowrap|September 2005}}".<ref>Green, Jesse. [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/03/theater/03Gree.html "She Sings! She Acts! She Prays!"] ''The New York Times'', {{Nowrap|December 3}}, 2006</ref> Chenoweth released an album in {{Nowrap|April 2005}}, ''[[As I Am (Kristin Chenoweth album)|As I Am]]'', a mixture of [[hymn]]s and [[contemporary Christian music]], with [[adult contemporary music|adult contemporary]] arrangements. To promote the album, she made an appearance on ''[[The 700 Club]]'', which upset some of her gay fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2011/09/kristin-chenoweth-christian-and-gay-rights-supporter/ |title=Kristin Chenoweth: Christian and Gay Rights Supporter |date=September 12, 2011 |last=Fisher |first=Luchina|access-date=April 7, 2017 |website=ABC News}}</ref> She later said she thought that the "[[Pat Robertson]]s and [[Jerry Falwell]]s of the world are scary" and that she regretted appearing on the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kristincanada.com/library/magazines.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080302113916/http://www.kristincanada.com/library/magazines.php| archive-date=March 2, 2008| title=The Kristin Library}}</ref>

In May 2010, Chenoweth wrote in response to [[Newsweek gay actor controversy|an article in ''Newsweek'']] by Ramin Setoodeh, an openly gay writer. Setoodeh thought that her Tony-nominated ''[[Promises, Promises (musical)|Promises, Promises]]'' co-star, [[Sean Hayes (actor)|Sean Hayes]], "comes off as wooden and insincere" in playing the straight character Chuck and that [[Jonathan Groff]] has a similar credibility problem in the TV show ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]''. He questioned whether any openly gay actor could acceptably portray a straight character.<ref>Setoodeh, Ramin. [https://web.archive.org/web/20110119121229/http://www.newsweek.com/2010/04/30/straight-jacket.html "Straight Jacket"]. ''Newsweek'', {{Nowrap|May 2010}}</ref> Chenoweth called the article "horrendously homophobic" and criticized Setoodeh's view as rationalizing "the same kind of bullying" that gay youths face in high school. Chenoweth argued that audiences "come to the theater to go on a journey" and do not care about an actor's sexual orientation.<ref>[http://www.autostraddle.com/chenoweth-defends-gay-actors-44570 "Kristen Chenoweth Stands Up for Gay Actors, Calls Out Homophobic ''Newsweek'' Article"].  Autostraddle.com, accessed {{Nowrap|May 9}}, 2010</ref> The story was discussed in media including ''The New York Times''<ref>Itzkoff, Dave. [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/11/theater/11arts-KRISTINCHENO_BRF.html "Kristin Chenoweth Has Some Words for Newsweek"]. ''The New York Times'', {{Nowrap|May 10}}, 2010</ref> and the ''Los Angeles Times''.<ref>Gornstein, Leslie. [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/gossip/2010/05/preach-it-kristin-chenoweth-homophobic-newsweek-letter.html "Preach It! Kristin Chenoweth does our job for us. Thanks, doll!"] ''Los Angeles Times'', {{Nowrap|May 10}}, 2010</ref>

Chenoweth has dated several men in Hollywood, including producer [[Dana Brunetti]],<ref>McRady, Rachel. [http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/kristin-chenoweth-boyfriend-dana-brunetti-split-exclusive-20141611 "Kristin Chenoweth, Boyfriend Dana Brunetti Split After Less Than a Year of Dating"], ''Us Weekly'', November 16, 2014</ref> actors [[Seth Green]], [[Lane Garrison]] and [[Marc Kudisch]] (to whom she was engaged from 1998 to 2001),<ref>Dugan, Christina. [https://people.com/tv/kristin-chenoweth-make-time-for-special-someone "Kristin Chenoweth Says She 'Has to Learn' to Balance Life and Make Time for a 'Special Someone'"], ''People'', July 20, 2018</ref> and producer/writer [[Aaron Sorkin]].<ref>Robinson, Joanna. [http://www.pajiba.com/miscellaneous/aaron-sorkin-continues-to-work-out-his-issues-with-exgirlfriends-through-his-show.php "Aaron Sorkin Continues to Work Out His Issues with Ex-Girlfriends Through His Show"], Pajiba.com, July 22, 2013, accessed January 21, 2015; Bardin, Brantley. [http://www.womenshealthmag.com/life/kristin-chenoweth-talks-to-womens-health "A Conversation with Singer-Actress Kristin Chenoweth"], November 8, 2006, accessed January 21, 2015</ref> In Sorkin's ''[[Studio 60 on the Sunset Strip]]'', the character of the Christian [[Harriet Hayes]] bears significant resemblances to Chenoweth, and the relationship between Hayes and "East coast liberal Jewish atheist" (Hayes' description) [[Matt Albie]] is modeled after that of Chenoweth and Sorkin. For example, Chenoweth's decision to appear on ''The 700 Club'' and her falling out with Women of Faith were depicted with the Hayes character.<ref name=NPR2009/><ref>Carter, Bill. [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/11/arts/television/11sork.html "''West Wing'' to West Coast: TV's Auteur Portrays TV"], ''The New York Times'', September 11, 2006, accessed January 21, 2015</ref> In 2018, Chenoweth began dating Josh Bryant, the guitarist for country band Backroad Anthem.<ref>Paul, Ranjita. [https://otakukart.com/kristin-chenoweth-boyfriend-the-actress-spotted-with-josh-bryant-at-a-charity-event "Kristin Chenoweth Boyfriend: The Actress Spotted With Josh Bryant at a Charity Event!"], Otakukart, July 23, 2021</ref> They became engaged in 2021<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/kristin-chenoweth-is-engaged-to-josh-bryant-now-that-ive-found-him-i-wont-let-him-go| title=Kristin Chenoweth Is Engaged to Josh Bryant: 'Now That I've Found Him, I Won't Let Him Go'|date=October 29, 2021|last=Bjornson|first=Greta|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211029203855/https://people.com/movies/kristin-chenoweth-is-engaged-to-josh-bryant-now-that-ive-found-him-i-wont-let-him-go| archive-date=October 29, 2021|url-status=live|access-date=October 29, 2021}}</ref> and were married on September 2, 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Kristin Chenoweth Is Married! Inside Her Pink Wedding to Josh Bryant in Texas: All the Details (Exclusive) |url=https://people.com/kristin-chenoweth-married-inside-her-pink-wedding-to-josh-bryant-exclusive-7964314 |access-date=September 3, 2023 |website=Peoplemag}}</ref>

